Q: Will it be harmonized with Quarto‚Äôs responsive behavior
Will it be harmonized with Quarto‚Äôs responsive behavior


A:
Yes ‚Äî using a media query like @media (min-width: 768px) isharmonized with Quarto‚Äôs responsive design. Here‚Äôs why:


‚úÖ Why it‚Äôs safe and harmonized:

Quarto uses Bootstrap 5 by default, which is fully responsiveand also uses standard breakpoints like 768px, 992px, etc.

So your @media (min-width: 768px) rule aligns exactly withBootstrap‚Äôs md breakpoint (medium devices and up).
This means your override will only apply on tablets andlarger, which fits well with Quarto‚Äôs layout behavior.

Mobile fallback remains untouched.

On mobile (below 768px), your rule won‚Äôt apply, and Quarto‚Äôsbuilt-in responsive image behavior will take over. This ensuresimages remain flexible and appropriately sized.

No layout breakage expected.

Your styling just constrains image size and centers it, withouthardcoding height or overriding container constraints.
This makes it non-invasive and safe to use alongside Quarto‚Äôsdefault theme logic.





üß™ You can confirm it‚Äôs working harmoniously by:

Opening DevTools ‚Üí Emulating different screen widths
Checking .lightbox img computed styles at &lt;768px vs ‚â•768px
Ensuring images stay within their container and don‚Äôt overflow orbecome blurry




Optional fine-tuning:
If you want images to scale smoothly between small and large screens,you could use a percentage-based max-width or clamp units:
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .lightbox img {
    max-width: clamp(300px, 50%, 500px) !important;
  }
}
